{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-12-28","name":"William Goare","nameForms":[{"lang":"und","fullText":"William Goare","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"William"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"Goare"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"alternateName":"Wlliam Goare","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1583–1609","fullLifespan":"1583–1609","portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/rq831/thumb200s.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"memoryArtifacts":[{"memoryType":"PHOTO","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-303-46940-432-49/dist.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/7756554","thumbnailUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-303-46940-432-49/thumb200s.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","deepZoomUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/deepzoomcloud/dzpatron/v1/TH-303-46940-432-49/scale?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","description":"Origin Displayed: English - Origins Available: English, French. Spelling variations of this family name include: Gore, Goare, Gorr, Core and others. First found in Essex where they were seated from early times and their first records appeared on the early census rolls taken by the early Kings of Britain to determine the rate of taxation of their subjects. Some of the first settlers of this family name or some of its variants were: John Gore settled in New England in 1630; Richard Gore settled in New England also in 1630; Steven Gore settled in Maryland in 1633; Thomas Gore was one of the earliest recorded settlers in the United States, he settled in Virginia in 1606. (From www.HouseOfNames.com Archives copyright  2000 - 2009) Motto Translated: The only safe course is to serve God. This interesting and unusual surname, with variant spellings Gore, Goare, Guare, Gur etc., derives from the Old English pre-7th Century \"gara\", a gore or triangular piece of land, and was originally given either as a topographical name to someone who lived by this natural feature, or as a locational name to one from Gore in Wiltshire or Gore Court in Kent. The surname was first recorded in the latter part of the 12th Century. Other early recordings include John de Gore, Cambridgeshire, 1257 and Alan ate Gore, the 1274 \"Hundred Rolls of Essex\". Recordings of the surname from London church registers include the marriage of Richard and Rachel Gore in St. Peter's Church, Cornhill, on 9 March 1520; the marriage of Raph Goare to Hellen Berick in St. Giles, Cripplegate, London on 15 December 1567 and the marriage of Samuel Gurr and Hannah Hurst in St. Clement Danes, Westminster, on 29 February 1772. The first recorded spelling of the family name is shown to be that of Ralph de la Gare, which was dated 1181, in the \"Pipe Rolls of Kent\", during the reign of King Henry 2nd, known as \"The Builder of Churches\", 1154 - 1189. Surnames became necessary when governments introduced personal taxation. In England this was known as Poll Tax. Throughout the centuries, surnames in every country have continued to \"develop\" often leading to astonishing variants of the original spelling.  Copyright: Name Origin Research www.surnamedb.com 1980 - 2014.","@type":"ImageObject"},{"memoryType":"PHOTO","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-303-46940-412-37/dist.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/7756510","thumbnailUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-303-46940-412-37/thumb200s.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","deepZoomUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/deepzoomcloud/dzpatron/v1/TH-303-46940-412-37/scale?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","description":"Origin Displayed: French - Origins Available: English, French. Spelling variations of this family name include: Jore, Joret, Joreau, Joriau, Joriaux, Jorin, Jorel, Jori, Jory, Jorry, Jorre, Jorret, Jorioz and many more. First found in Normandy. Some of the first settlers of this family name or some of its variants were: Edouard Jory who settled in Virginia in 1664; and Louis Jorel de la Louisiere who was buried in Quebec in 1726. (From www.HouseOfNames.com Archives copyright  2000 - 2009). This interesting and unusual surname, with variant spellings Gore, Goare, Guare, Gur etc., derives from the Old English pre-7th Century \"gara\", a gore or triangular piece of land, and was originally given either as a topographical name to someone who lived by this natural feature, or as a locational name to one from Gore in Wiltshire or Gore Court in Kent. The surname was first recorded in the latter part of the 12th Century. Other early recordings include John de Gore, Cambridgeshire, 1257 and Alan ate Gore, the 1274 \"Hundred Rolls of Essex\". Recordings of the surname from London church registers include the marriage of Richard and Rachel Gore in St. Peter's Church, Cornhill, on 9 March 1520; the marriage of Raph Goare to Hellen Berick in St. Giles, Cripplegate, London on 15 December 1567 and the marriage of Samuel Gurr and Hannah Hurst in St. Clement Danes, Westminster, on 29 February 1772. The first recorded spelling of the family name is shown to be that of Ralph de la Gare, which was dated 1181, in the \"Pipe Rolls of Kent\", during the reign of King Henry 2nd, known as \"The Builder of Churches\", 1154 - 1189. Surnames became necessary when governments introduced personal taxation. In England this was known as Poll Tax. Throughout the centuries, surnames in every country have continued to \"develop\" often leading to astonishing variants of the original spelling.  Copyright: Name Origin Research www.surnamedb.com 1980 - 2014.","@type":"ImageObject"}],"birthDate":"+1583","birthPlace":{"address":"Cattistock, Dorset, England","geo":{"latitude":50.7975,"longitude":-2.5821,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"christeningDate":"+1583-06-16","christeningPl