16 June 1583","22 November 1608":"22 November 1608","ABT 1605":"about 1605","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","<Cattistock, Dorset, England>":"Cattistock, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Cattistock, Dorset, England":"Cattistock, Dorset, England","Cattistock,Dorset,England":"Cattistock, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Goare","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Hoar  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hoar","meanings":["English (Hampshire):","nickname from Middle English <i>hor(e)</i> ‘gray- or white-haired’ (Old English <i>hār</i>). This name has been established in Ireland since the late 13th century and was Gaelicized as <b>de Hóir</b> and <b>de Hóra</b>.","habitational name from Ore (Sussex), or else a topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) bank’, from Middle English <i>or(e)</i> ‘brink, edge’ (Old English <i>ōra</i>)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":2,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":4,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":17,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Goare was born in 1583, in Cattistock, Dorset, England, his father, Goare, was 24 and his mother, Mrs. Jerrard Goare, was 21. He married Elizabeth Collier about 1605, in Cattistock, Dorset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1609, in Dorset, England, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1583–1609":"1583–1609","1587–Female":"1587–Surnud","1608–Male":"1608–Surnud","1609–1653":"1609–1653","1560–Male":"1560–Surnud","1562–Female":"1562–Surnud","1600":"1600","1653":"1653","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","1583":"1583","1609":"1609","1560":"1560","1608":"1608","16 June 1583":"16. juuni 1583","22 November 1608":"22. november 1608","ABT 1605":"umbes 1605","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middles